   <div class="lbl">Article 4-1003.C.1.d — Termination Trigger</div>
   <h3>Three independent grounds for termination</h3>
   <ol>
     <li><strong>Traffic intensification</strong> — Truck trips rose from ~37 ADT (1994 baseline) to 303+ ADT in 2023 and 498–625 ADT in 2024–26 — a 700%+ increase, by CEMEX's own data.</li>
-    <li><strong>Physical expansion</strong> — Dozens of new structures built since 19941990s-era standards: telecommunications towers on silos, dust collectors, electrical upgrades, drilling wells (documented in the New Structures evidence file).</li>
+    <li><strong>Physical expansion</strong> — Dozens of new structures built since 1994 without required permits: telecommunications towers on silos, dust collector systems, electrical upgrades, drilling wells, and signage (all documented in the New Structures evidence file).</li>
     <li><strong>Changed character of use</strong> — A conveyor-fed quarry operation (limestone and shale moved by enclosed belt across Highway 66 from Dowe Flats) was transformed into a truck-import operation hauling raw materials from Wyoming ~250 miles away.</li>
   </ol>
   <p style="margin-top:14px;font-size:.92rem;opacity:.8">If <em>any</em> of these three grounds is proven, the right to continue the nonconforming use "terminates immediately." The County's burden-of-proof framework under the Code puts the onus on the property owner — not the community — to show the use hasn't changed.</p>
